{
  format: 1
  name: json-object-orders-by-sorted-keys-then-values
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.3", "§A.7"]
  tags: ["ordering", "json"]
  note: '''
    §B.3 object order: "keys sorted by text order, then lexicographic
    (key, value) pair order". Canonical JSON already sorts object keys by text
    order (A.7), so member insertion order in the seed is irrelevant. The trap
    is that the KEY dominates the value: a smaller value under a larger key
    does not win.

    Seeded objects and their canonical (key,value) pair sequences:
      {a:1}       -> [(a,1)]
      {a:1, b:0}  -> [(a,1),(b,0)]
      {a:2}       -> [(a,2)]
      {b:1}       -> [(b,1)]
    Comparisons:
      {a:1} < {a:1,b:0}   shared prefix (a,1), shorter first
      {a:1,b:0} < {a:2}   first pair (a,1) vs (a,2): key equal, 1 < 2
      {a:2} < {b:1}       first pair key a < key b, so {a:2} precedes {b:1}
                          even though its value 2 is larger than 1
    The last line is the attack: {b:1} sorts LAST despite holding the smallest
    value, because key "b" > key "a". `b_first` is seeded with members written
    b-before-a to also prove key canonicalization ignores authoring order.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.jsonobj@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      rows: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        o: "json"
      }
      $public: {
        by_o: { $view: ".rows { id, o, $sort: [o] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      rows: {
        r_b1: { o: { b: 1 } }
        r_a2: { o: { a: 2 } }
        r_a1b0: { o: { b: 0, a: 1 } }
        r_a1: { o: { a: 1 } }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.by_o", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { id: "r_a1", o: { a: 1 } }
        { id: "r_a1b0", o: { a: 1, b: 0 } }
        { id: "r_a2", o: { a: 2 } }
        { id: "r_b1", o: { b: 1 } }
      ] } }
  ]
}
